Text: OMG!  Itâ€™s frustrating that those women don't know how to respond to him, they even say Iâ€™m not a feminist! As itâ€™s a bad word!!!! ğŸ¤¦ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸  First of all, we need to correct the misconception about feminism for those who misunderstand it. Feminism is not against men, it is not against religion, and it does not advocate nudity for women. Feminism simply demands power-sharing and decision-making in all fields with women, instead of it solely being in the hands of men.  Feminism does not deny biological differences, nor does it seek biological equality, as that is impossible. In the end, men cannot carry a child, and women do not possess the same muscular ability as men (unless trained). Additionally, feminism acknowledges that power has historically been in the hands of men.. and calls for men to share this power in order to achieve justice and amplify women's voices in all fields. Therefore, we cannot eliminate men, but we need to share responsibilities to achieve justice, and to make it easier even to the man.  When he mentioned that feminism cannot completely do away with men because women use phones made by men and drive cars made by men, firstly, that is true!  Neither women can do without men, nor men can do without women. Secondly, that is exactly what feminism advocates! It aims to enhance the role of women in inventions, discoveries, and entrepreneurship. When you say women use things created or invented by men, it means that in previous eras, power was primarily in the hands of men, which diminished the role of women in these inventions and hindered their contributions. Women were not even given the right to think. However, now we can clearly see successful women as inventors, discoverers, and business leaders due to the efforts of feminist movements in enhancing women's roles.  Regarding the point that women cannot defend themselves in wars, this is true because in most countries, women are not extensively trained in the military as men are. So itâ€™s why that men have a greater ability to participate in wars, and women seek protection. Therefore, we also demand that women be trained to support men in wars. Ultimately, women are fully capable physically and mentally, and with intensive training, they can defend themselves and their countries.  I reiterate that feminism does not deny the biological differences between genders, but it only calls for justice in rights and duties.  It is enough to distort and diminish the value of these great efforts that have been made to defend and enhance women's position. Spreading misconceptions that feminism is against men and wants to completely do away with them contradicts logic altogether.

Text: Allah says  in quran  4:3) If you fear that you might not treat the orphans justly, then marry the women that seem good to you: two, or three, or four.4 If you fear that you will not be able to treat them justly, then marry (only) one,5 or marry from among those whom your right hands possess.6 This will make it more likely that you will avoid injustice. (surah An-Nisa  4:3).    it's necessary for a correct understanding of the Quran. Here is how they explain Q. 4:3:  (i) There is the view of 'A'ishah who says that men tended to marry orphan girls who were under their guardianship out of consideration for either their property, beauty or because they thought they would be able to treat them according to their whims, as they had no one to protect them. After marriage such men sometimes committed excesses against these girls. It is in this context that the Muslims are told that if they fear they will not be able to do justice to the orphan girls, then they should marry other girls whom they like. (This interpretation seems to be supported by (verse 127 )of this surah.)  (ii) The second view is that of Ibn 'Abbas and his disciple 'Ikrimah who expressed the opinion that in the Jahiliyah period there was no limit on the number of wives a man could take. The result was that a man sometimes married as many as ten women and, when expenses increased because of a large family, he encroached on the rights either of his orphan nephews or other relatives. It was in this context that God fixed the limit of four wives and instructed the Muslims that they may marry up to four wives providing they possessed the capacity to treat them equitably.  (iii) Sa'id b. Jubayr, Qatadah and some other commentators say that while the Arabs of the Jahiliyah period did not approve of subjecting orphans to wrong, they had no concept of justice and equity with regard to women. They married as many women as they wanted and then subjected them to injustice and oppression. It is in this context that people are told that if they fear perpetrating wrongs on orphans they ought to be equally worried about perpetrating them on women. In the first place they should never marry more than four, and of those four, they should marry only as many as they can treat fairly.  Each of the three interpretations is plausible and all three may possibly be correct. Moreover, the verse could also mean that if a person does not find himself able to treat orphans in a fair manner, then he might as well marry the women who are looking after those orphans.  5. Muslim jurists are agreed that according to this verse the maximum number Of wives has been fixed at four. This conclusion is also supported by traditions. It is reported that when Ghaylan, the chief of Ta'if, embraced Islam he had nine wives. The Prophet (peace be on him) ordered him to keep only four wives and divorce the rest. Another person, Nawfal b. Mu'awiyah, had five wives. The Prophet (peace be on him) ordered him to divorce one of them. (For the relevant traditions see the comments of Ibn Kathir and Qurtubi on this verse - Ed.)  This verse stipulates that marrying more wives than one is permissible on the condition that one treats his wives equitably. A person who avails himself of this permission granted by God to have a plurality of wives, and disregards the condition laid down by God to treat them equitably has not acted in good faith with God. In case there are complaints from wives that they are not being treated equitably, the Islamic state has the right to intervene and redress such grievances.  Some people who have been overwhelmed and overawed by the Christianized outlook of Westerners have tried to prove that the real aim of the Qur'an was to put an end to polygamy (which, in their opinion, is intrinsically evil). Since it was widely practised at that time, however, Islam confined itself to placing restrictions on it. Such arguments only show the mental slavery to which these people have succumbed. That polygamy is an evil per se is an unacceptable proposition, for under certain conditions it becomes a moral and social necessity. If polygamy is totally prohibited men who cannot remain satisfied with only one wife will look outside the bounds of matrimonial life and create sexual anarchy and corruption. This is likely to cause much greater harm than polygamy to the moral and social order. For this reason the Qur'an has allowed those who feel the need for it to resort to polygamy. Those who consider it an evil in itself may certainly denounce it in disregard of the Qur'an and may even argue for its abolition. But they have no right to attribute such a view to the Qur'an, for it has expressed its permission of polygamy in quite categorical terms. Indeed, there is not the slightest hint in the Qur'an that could justify the conclusion that it advocates abolition of polygamy. (For further elaboration see my book, Sunnat k A'iniHaythiyat, Lahore, 3rd edition, 1975, pp. 307-16.)  6. This expression denotes 'slave-girls', i.e. female captives of war who are distributed by the state among individuals. The purpose of this verse is to tell men that if their financial circumstances do not permit them to support a free woman as their wife then they may marry a slave-girl (see verse 25 below); if they consider it necessary to have more than one wife and it would be difficult for them to treat their free wives equitably they may resort to slave-girls, for here the burden of obligations is lighter by comparison. (For further injunctions regarding slave-girls seen. 44 below.)

Text:
@Fyrdman The crime rate has not increased, that's not true. The overall crime rate has not changed much since the 70's, the murder rate has even dropped significantly.

The reason people could afford a lot of things in the '50s is because the war boosted the economy, but after that boost the economy just went back to a more natural course. Before the war, the economy was not so good.

Invention and innovation did not stagnate. Stagnation means no activity, no growth, or a state of stillness, and by that definition it is false - there is innovation: AI, image recognition, the self-driving cars, and the first successful fusion reactions with net energy gains. All this means that human civilization is progressing.

"Rampant degeneracy" What do you mean by degeneracy?

Also, what you are basically describing does not amount to the destruction of civilization. It's just a change in culture, which is fine because culture is constantly changing, and if it wasn't changing, it would be stagnation.

"As for women, you can look around for all sorts of privileges" Okay, then it's not "handouts" but privileges. Most privileges are needed because women are mostly discriminated against. Employers quite often won't hire a woman because they're afraid she might take a year of maternity leave, which is terrible from an employer's perspective because it takes a decent amount of time to train an employee and then have to find a replacement after that. Hiring quotas are a good thing because it allows more women to have a source of income so they can raise children. Society needs more people to sustain itself.

The lack of a draft for women is a good thing because from the government's perspective, women are much more valuable than men, given that women can have children and men can't.

"Politicians and orgs working to change laws and social mores in their favor" And there is a good reason politicians do that, because it is good; women do need support. The easier life for women, the more incentive they have to raise children; without money, they couldn't do it.

That Curie stole her accomplishments makes no sense, since she continued to work hard after her husband's death in 1906. What exactly did she steal in 1911? Also, how could she have stolen anything at all during WWI, when she worked hard during that time and then, having gained experience during WWI, developed mobile radiography.

Tate appears to have bought into all the hype regarding himself. (Gen. 21:2, 12; 24:67) Isaacâ€™s son Jacob, however, had two wives, due to trickery on the part of his father-in-law Laban. Jacob also had concubines.â€‹â€”Gen. 29:21-29; 30:1-13.  So when the Law came in, it did not bring in polygamy or concubinage, nor did it encourage these practices. In fact, polygamy was evidently not practiced by the majority in ancient Israel; primarily it was confined to the more prominent and wealthy, though not to these exclusively. (Judg. 8:30; 2 Chron. 11:21) For kings to have many wives was sort of a â€˜status symbolâ€™ among the nations.â€‹â€”2 Sam. 16:20-22.  References in the Psalms, Proverbs and Ecclesiastes to happy marriages seem to take for granted the monogamous state. â€œRejoice with the wife of your youth,â€ says Proverbs 5:18. And Ecclesiastes 9:9 counsels: â€œSee life with the wife whom you love all the days of your vain life that He has given you under the sun.â€ (Compare Psalm 128; Proverbs 18:22; 31:10-31.) Furthermore, the danger of polygamy was stressed in Godâ€™s counsel to kings: â€œHe [the king] should also not multiply wives for himself, that his heart may not turn aside.â€ (Deut. 17:17) King Solomon ignored this warning, to his sorrow.â€‹â€”1 Ki. 11:4-6.

Text:
@Shannon Beyers It doesn't sound like if we disagree all that much. I'm not religious, so that stuff is fine but it doesn't hold any particular weight to me. And even you said that he sure puts on a spectacle. That's exactly what he does and it's a big part of why he has become so well-known. He masterfully intertwines pretty obvious stuff and facts with sarcasm, irony, and the more over-the-top sides of his online persona. That includes the yelling and I'm the most confident and alpha person in the building! It makes you feel things. It makes you think about and question the status quo.

A very calm, plain and academic conversation would get 100 views and ultimately have no impact on the world. Whether you like it or not, the way he does things has clearly been a massive success. People clearly respond to it. It grabs people's attention. It has given millions of disenfranchised young men - mainly - a role model to look up to and motivate them to level up and keep going even if their current lives aren't what they would've liked currently. If it takes some crude jokes, an over-the-top online persona and some yelling, then that's a fairly small price to pay for so much good on a global scale.

Finally, I just wanted to point out that while I'm not religious, the main religions have been around for a long time now. They've survived, unlike many that have been left behind along the way. So regardless of any divine powers, they seem to contain some kind of good-practice for a long-term thriving society. Rather than completely shun it all, maybe it would be worth considering what those things are?
Same thing with what you called a call "Caveman" stuff. I don't hear Tate or anyone really pushing us to a primitive caveman existence. I honestly think that's a case of you maybe getting so hung up on how he says things that you manage to miss what he's actually saying. His point is that biology is real, and our biological needs and proclivities are a big part of what drives us to want what we want and choose what we choose. Whether we're aware of it or not. No amount of technological advancement or academic studying will undo that anytime soon. It is part of who and what we are. It's part of how we made it to here.

In both cases, the behaviors that have been successful long-term have survived and thrived. The choices that have been successful long-term have survived and thrived. That's why society has been shaped the way it has. I believe that a big part of that is that different people have different strength and weaknesses. That doesn't mean that one person's value as a human is any greater or lesser than the next person, or that people don't deserve basic respect, only that we have different purposes and that our greatest contribution to society is in different areas. As a greater society, we are much stronger together pulling in the same direction, than with everyone off on their own little self-absorbed island running their own race. It's what makes us different that makes us compliment each other so well. Only when we acknowledge that and accept our place in the greater picture can we be happy and be the best version of ourselves. Only then can our society thrive at its fullest capacity.
Author: Max Power

Text:
@Hamza Siddiqui Again, projection.

But it's more complicated when it comes to insecurity. Women get insecure all the time about all kinds of things. Men get insecure about being able to protect their genetic investment.
Men get loyal in a way, or to a degree, that women don't. Once they have bonded with a woman, they can become insecure if they get the feeling that the woman isn't as loyal as they are. They had planned to raise a son, pass on his hunting skills, and has some expectation that the son will take care of him and the mother as they get older. I'm speaking of evolutionary motivation, instincts. The other strategy is the sowing of wild oats. The young man may invest very little in a bunch of possible offspring, but usually when he gets older he will adjust to the other strategy. Women fall in the middle of those two strategies. She knows for sure the baby is hers, but she is incapacitated while pregnant and until the kid can be helpful, so she needs a man to feed and protect her and her child, but she needs to be psychologically able to quickly shift to another man, because part of her man's job is to put his life at risk for her, and occasionally the man loses. She needs to be alert for any signs of weakness, illness or loss of interest, so she can shift gears ASAP.
This is a really crude/low resolution explanation, and if there's one word that describes everything human it is 'exceptions', but I hope you can see source of the three psychological patterns. I'm not accusing, forgiving, or even judging people here, a lot of this is subconscious.
